    <body>

        <div rend="parallel">
          <p xml:id="AN177.1-kilavi">uṟaiyūr iṉampoṉvāṇikaṉ <app><lem>cāttaṅkō</lem><rdg wit="#C9v">cāttaṅkoṟṟaṉ</rdg><rdg wit="#C7">cāttaṅkoṟṟaṉār</rdg></app> piriviṭai vēṟupaṭṭa talaimakaḷait tōḻi vaṟpuṟuttiyatu.</p>
          <p xml:lang="en">How the confidante consoled HER who had undergone changes in the time of separation.</p>
        </div>
        <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="AN177.1">
        <l>toṉṉalañ citaiyac cā<supplied>a</supplied> yalkalu</l>
        <l>miṉṉum vārā riṉiyevaṉ ceykeṉap</l>
        <l>perumpulam puṟuta lōmpumati ciṟuka</l>
        <l>ṇirumpiṭit taṭakkai māṉa neyyarun</l>
        <l>toruṅkupiṇit tiyaṉṟa veṟiko ḷaimpāṟ</l>
        <l>ṟēṅkamaḻ veṟimalar peymmār kāmpiṉ</l>
        <l>kaḻaiyamal cilampiṉ vaḻaitalai vāṭak</l>
        <l>katirkataṅ kaṟṟa vēka ṉeṭiyiṭaip</l>
        <l>paiṅkoṭip pāka<supplied>ṟ</supplied> ceṅkaṉi nacaiik</l>
        <l>kāṉa maññaik kama<supplied>ñcūl</supplied> māppeṭai</l>
        <l>yaviriyāṟ ṟaṭaikarai vayi<supplied>ri</supplied> ṉaraluṅ</l>
        <l>kāṭiṟan takaṉṟōr nīṭiṉa rāyiṉum</l>
        <l>vallē varuvar pōlum veṉvē</l>
        <l>lilainiṟam peyara vōcci māṟṟōr</l>
        <l>malaimaruḷ yāṉai maṇṭama roḻitta</l>
        <l>kaḻaṟ<supplied>kā</supplied>ṟ paṇṇaṉ kāviri vaṭa<supplied>va</supplied>yi</l>
        <l>ṉiḻaṟkayan taḻī<supplied>iya</supplied> neṭuṅkāṉ māvi<supplied>ṉ</supplied></l>
        <l>ṟaḷirē rākan takaipeṟa mukainta</l>
        <l>vaṇaṅkuṭai vaṉamulait tāyaniṉ</l>
        <l>cuṇaṅkaṭai varinta toyyila niṉaintē.</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
        <l>“Exhausted so that [my] old beauty is spoiled, all night, (1)</l>
        <l>even now he does not come. Now, what will I do?”, saying so, (2)</l>
        <l>beware of feeling great loneliness! (3a-c)</l>
        <l>In order to put perfumed blossoms smelling of honey (6a-c)</l>
        <l>in [your] perfumed [hair in] five parts that was made up by tying [it] together, (5)</l>
        <l>absorbing oil, resembling the broad trunk of the small-eyed dark she-elephant, (3d-4)</l>
        <l>he who departed traversing the wilderness, (12ab)</l>
        <l>where, on the way long to go that has learned the [sun] rays’ anger (8)</l>
        <l>when the tops of the gamboge faded on the mountain side thickly grown with bamboo,</l>
        <l rend="indent8">pleasing with [its] stalks, (6df.)</l>
        <l>the fully pregnant dark female of the forest peacock, (10)</l>
        <l>yearning for the red fruit of the Pākal in fresh creepers, (9)</l>
        <l>calls out like a bugle on the setting shore of the shining river (11)</l>
        <l rend="indent8">even if he is delayed, (12cd)</l>
        <l>he will come [back] quickly, it seems, (13a-c)</l>
        <l>– thinking of the sandel paste [marks] that are outlined near your beauty spots, (20)</l>
        <l>to be spread on the tormenting beautiful breasts (19)</l>
        <l>that budded befittingly on [your] bosom that resembles [in colour] the sprouts (18)</l>
        <l>of the large-trunked mango tree that embraces the shady pond (17)</l>
        <l>on the northern side of the Kāviri of Paṇṇaṉ, with anklets on [his] legs, (16)</l>
        <l>who ended the battle by spearing the mountain-like elephants (15)</l>
        <l>of the enemies, raising [his] victorious spear</l> 
        <l rend="indent8">so that [its] leaf[-shaped] tip moves into the vital spot. (13df.)</l>
      </lg>
